INTRODUCTORY	1
NOTE	1
By	1
Professor	1
J.	1
Arthur	1
Thomson	1
Was	1
it	1
not	1
the	1
great	1
philosopher	1
and	1
mathematician	1
Leibnitz	1
who	1
said	1
that	1
the	1
more	1
knowledge	1
advances	1
the	1
more	1
it	1
becomes	1
possible	1
to	1
condense	1
it	1
into	1
little	1
books?	1
Now	1
this	1
"Outline	1
of	1
Science"	1
is	1
certainly	1
not	1
a	1
little	1
book,	1
and	1
yet	1
it	1
illustrates	1
part	1
of	1
the	1
meaning	1
of	1
Leibnitz's	1
wise	1
saying.	1
For	1
here	1
within	1
reasonable	1
compass	1
there	1
is	1
a	1
library	1
of	1
little	1
books--an	1
outline	1
of	1
many	1
sciences.	1
It	1
will	1
be	1
profitable	1
to	1
the	1
student	1
in	1
proportion	1
to	1
the	1
discrimination	1
with	1
which	1
it	1
is	1
used.	1
For	1
it	1
is	1
not	1
in	1
the	1
least	1
meant	1
to	1
be	1
of	1
the	1
nature	1
of	1
an	1
Encyclopæa,	1
giving	1
condensed	1
and	1
comprehensive	1
articles	1
with	1
a	1
big	1
full	1
stop	1
at	1
the	1
end	1
of	1
each.	1
Nor	1
is	1
it	1
a	1
collection	1
of	1
"primers,"	1
beginning	1
at	1
the	1
very	1
beginning	1
of	1
each	1
subject	1
and	1
working	1
methodically	1
onwards.	1
That	1
is	1
not	1
the	1
idea.	1
What	1
then	1
is	1
the	1
aim	1
of	1
this	1
book?	1
It	1
is	1
to	1
give	1
the	1
intelligent	1
student-citizen,	1
otherwise	1
called	1
"the	1
man	1
in	1
the	1
street,"	1
a	1
bunch	1
of	1
intellectual	1
keys	1
by	1
which	1
to	1
open	1
doors	1
which	1
have	1
been	1
hitherto	1
shut	1
to	1
him,	1
partly	1
because	1
he	1
got	1
no	1
glimpse	1
of	1
the	1
treasures	1
behind	1
the	1
doors,	1
and	1
partly	1
because	1
the	1
portals	1
were	1
made	1
forbidding	1
by	1
an	1
unnecessary	1
display	1
of	1
technicalities.	1
Laying	1
aside	1
conventional	1
modes	1
of	1
treatment	1
and	1
seeking	1
rather	1
to	1
open	1
up	1
the	1
subject	1
as	1
one	1
might	1
on	1
a	1
walk	1
with	1
a	1
friend,	1
the	1
work	1
offers	1
the	1
student	1
what	1
might	1
be	1
called	1
informal	1
introductions	1
to	1
the	1
various	1
departments	1
of	1
knowledge.	1
To	1
put	1
it	1
in	1
another	1
way,	1
the	1
articles	1
are	1
meant	1
to	1
be	1
clues	1
which	1
the	1
reader	1
may	1
follow	1
till	1
he	1
has	1
left	1
his	1
starting	1
point	1
very	1
far	1
behind.	1
Perhaps	1
when	1
he	1
has	1
gone	1
far	1
on	1
his	1
own	1
he	1
will	1
not	1
be	1
ungrateful	1
to	1
the	1
simple	1
book	1
of	1
"instructions	1
to	1
travellers"	1
which	1
this	1
"Outline	1
of	1
Science"	1
is	1
intended	1
to	1
be.	1
The	1
simple	1
"bibliographies"	1
appended	1
to	1
the	1
various	1
articles	1
will	1
be	1
enough	1
to	1
indicate	1
"first	1
books."	1
Each	1
article	1
is	1
meant	1
to	1
be	1
an	1
invitation	1
to	1
an	1
intellectual	1
adventure,	1
and	1
the	1
short	1
lists	1
of	1
books	1
are	1
merely	1
finger-posts	1
for	1
the	1
beginning	1
of	1
the	1
journey.	1
We	1
confess	1
to	1
being	1
greatly	1
encouraged	1
by	1
the	1
reception	1
that	1
has	1
been	1
given	1
to	1
the	1
English	1
serial	1
issue	1
of	1
"The	1
Outline	1
of	1
Science."	1
It	1
has	1
been	1
very	1
hearty--we	1
might	1
almost	1
say	1
enthusiastic.	1
For	1
we	1
agree	1
with	1
Professor	1
John	1
Dewey,	1
that	1
"the	1
future	1
of	1
our	1
civilisation	1
depends	1
upon	1
the	1
widening	1
spread	1
and	1
deepening	1
hold	1
of	1
the	1
scientific	1
habit	1
of	1
mind."	1
And	1
we	1
hope	1
that	1
this	1
is	1
what	1
"The	1
Outline	1
of	1
Science"	1
makes	1
for.	1
Information	1
is	1
all	1
to	1
the	1
good;	1
interesting	1
information	1
is	1
better	1
still;	1
but	1
best	1
of	1
all	1
is	1
the	1
education	1
of	1
the	1
scientific	1
habit	1
of	1
mind.	1
Another	1
modern	1
philosopher,	1
Professor	1
L.	1
T.	1
Hobhouse,	1
has	1
declared	1
that	1
the	1
evolutionist's	1
mundane	1
goal	1
is	1
"the	1
mastery	1
by	1
the	1
human	1
mind	1
of	1
the	1
conditions,	1
internal	1
as	1
well	1
as	1
external,	1
of	1
its	1
life	1
and	1
growth."	1
Under	1
the	1
influence	1
of	1
this	1
conviction	1
"The	1
Outline	1
of	1
Science"	1
has	1
been	1
written.	1
For	1
life	1
is	1
not	1
for	1
science,	1
but	1
science	1
for	1
life.	1
And	1
even	1
more	1
than	1
science,	1
to	1
our	1
way	1
of	1
thinking,	1
is	1
the	1
individual	1
development	1
of	1
the	1
scientific	1
way	1
of	1
looking	1
at	1
things.	1
Science	1
is	1
our	1
legacy;	1
we	1
must	1
use	1
it	1
if	1
it	1
is	1
to	1
be	1
our	1
very	1
own.	1
