THE	1
AEGIR	1
ON	1
THE	1
TRENT	1
291	1
Photo:	1
G.	1
Brocklehurst.	1
The	1
Outline	1
of	1
Science	1
INTRODUCTION	1
There	1
is	1
abundant	1
evidence	1
of	1
a	1
widened	1
and	1
deepened	1
interest	1
in	1
modern	1
science.	1
How	1
could	1
it	1
be	1
otherwise	1
when	1
we	1
think	1
of	1
the	1
magnitude	1
and	1
the	1
eventfulness	1
of	1
recent	1
advances?	1
But	1
the	1
interest	1
of	1
the	1
general	1
public	1
would	1
be	1
even	1
greater	1
than	1
it	1
is	1
if	1
the	1
makers	1
of	1
new	1
knowledge	1
were	1
more	1
willing	1
to	1
expound	1
their	1
discoveries	1
in	1
ways	1
that	1
could	1
be	1
"understanded	1
of	1
the	1
people."	1
No	1
one	1
objects	1
very	1
much	1
to	1
technicalities	1
in	1
a	1
game	1
or	1
on	1
board	1
a	1
yacht,	1
and	1
they	1
are	1
clearly	1
necessary	1
for	1
terse	1
and	1
precise	1
scientific	1
description.	1
It	1
is	1
certain,	1
however,	1
that	1
they	1
can	1
be	1
reduced	1
to	1
a	1
minimum	1
without	1
sacrificing	1
accuracy,	1
when	1
the	1
object	1
in	1
view	1
is	1
to	1
explain	1
"the	1
gist	1
of	1
the	1
matter."	1
So	1
this	1
OUTLINE	1
OF	1
SCIENCE	1
is	1
meant	1
for	1
the	1
general	1
reader,	1
who	1
lacks	1
both	1
time	1
and	1
opportunity	1
for	1
special	1
study,	1
and	1
yet	1
would	1
take	1
an	1
intelligent	1
interest	1
in	1
the	1
progress	1
of	1
science	1
which	1
is	1
making	1
the	1
world	1
always	1
new.	1
The	1
story	1
of	1
the	1
triumphs	1
of	1
modern	1
science	1
is	1
one	1
of	1
which	1
Man	1
may	1
well	1
be	1
proud.	1
Science	1
reads	1
the	1
secret	1
of	1
the	1
distant	1
star	1
and	1
anatomises	1
the	1
atom;	1
foretells	1
the	1
date	1
of	1
the	1
comet's	1
return	1
and	1
predicts	1
the	1
kinds	1
of	1
chickens	1
that	1
will	1
hatch	1
from	1
a	1
dozen	1
eggs;	1
discovers	1
the	1
laws	1
of	1
the	1
wind	1
that	1
bloweth	1
where	1
it	1
