§	1
2	1
The	1
Surface	1
of	1
the	1
Sun	1
Here	1
let	1
us	1
return	1
to	1
and	1
see	1
what	1
more	1
we	1
know	1
about	1
the	1
photosphere--the	1
sun's	1
surface.	1
It	1
is	1
from	1
the	1
photosphere	1
that	1
we	1
have	1
gained	1
most	1
of	1
our	1
knowledge	1
of	1
the	1
composition	1
of	1
the	1
sun,	1
which	1
is	1
believed	1
not	1
to	1
be	1
a	1
solid	1
body.	1
Examination	1
of	1
the	1
photosphere	1
shows	1
that	1
the	1
outer	1
surface	1
is	1
never	1
at	1
rest.	1
Small	1
bright	1
cloudlets	1
come	1
and	1
go	1
in	1
rapid	1
succession,	1
giving	1
the	1
surface,	1
through	1
contrasts	1
in	1
luminosity,	1
a	1
granular	1
appearance.	1
Of	1
course,	1
to	1
be	1
visible	1
at	1
all	1
at	1
92,830,000	1
miles	1
the	1
cloudlets	1
cannot	1
be	1
small.	1
They	1
imply	1
enormous	1
activity	1
in	1
the	1
photosphere.	1
If	1
we	1
might	1
speak	1
picturesquely	1
the	1
sun's	1
surface	1
resembles	1
a	1
boiling	1
ocean	1
of	1
white-hot	1
metal	1
vapours.	1
We	1
have	1
to-day	1
a	1
wonderful	1
instrument,	1
which	1
will	1
be	1
described	1
later,	1
which	1
dilutes,	1
as	1
it	1
were,	1
the	1
general	1
glare	1
of	1
the	1
sun,	1
and	1
enables	1
us	1
to	1
observe	1
these	1
fiery	1
eruptions	1
at	1
any	1
hour.	1
The	1
"oceans"	1
of	1
red-hot	1
gas	1
and	1
white-hot	1
metal	1
vapour	1
at	1
the	1
sun's	1
surface	1
are	1
constantly	1
driven	1
by	1
great	1
storms.	1
Some	1
unimaginable	1
energy	1
streams	1
out	1
from	1
the	1
body	1
or	1
muscles	1
of	1
the	1
sun	1
and	1
blows	1
its	1
outer	1
layers	1
into	1
gigantic	1
shreds,	1
as	1
it	1
were.	1
The	1
actual	1
temperature	1
at	1
the	1
sun's	1
surface,	1
or	1
what	1
appears	1
to	1
us	1
to	1
be	1
the	1
surface--the	1
photosphere--is,	1
of	1
course,	1
unknown,	1
but	1
careful	1
calculation	1
suggests	1
that	1
it	1
is	1
from	1
5,000°	1
C.	1
to	1
7,000°	1
C.	1
The	1
interior	1
is	1
vastly	1
hotter.	1
We	1
can	1
form	1
no	1
conception	1
of	1
such	1
temperatures	1
as	1
must	1
exist	1
there.	1
Not	1
even	1
the	1
most	1
obdurate	1
solid	1
could	1
resist	1
such	1
temperatures,	1
but	1
would	1
be	1
converted	1
almost	1
instantaneously	1
into	1
gas.	1
But	1
it	1
would	1
not	1
be	1
gas	1
as	1
we	1
know	1
gases	1
on	1
the	1
earth.	1
The	1
enormous	1
pressures	1
that	1
exist	1
on	1
the	1
sun	1
must	1
convert	1
even	1
gases	1
into	1
thick	1
treacly	1
fluids.	1
We	1
can	1
only	1
infer	1
this	1
state	1
of	1
matter.	1
It	1
is	1
beyond	1
our	1
power	1
to	1
reproduce	1
it.	1
Sun-spots	1
It	1
is	1
in	1
the	1
brilliant	1
photosphere	1
that	1
the	1
dark	1
areas	1
known	1
as	1
sun-spots	1
appear.	1
Some	1
of	1
these	1
dark	1
spots--they	1
are	1
dark	1
only	1
by	1
contrast	1
with	1
the	1
photosphere	1
surrounding	1
them--are	1
of	1
enormous	1
size,	1
covering	1
many	1
thousands	1
of	1
square	1
miles	1
of	1
surface.	1
What	1
they	1
are	1
we	1
cannot	1
positively	1
say.	1
They	1
look	1
like	1
great	1
cavities	1
in	1
the	1
sun's	1
surface.	1
Some	1
think	1
they	1
are	1
giant	1
whirlpools.	1
Certainly	1
they	1
seem	1
to	1
be	1
great	1
whirling	1
streams	1
of	1
glowing	1
gases	1
with	1
vapours	1
above	1
them	1
and	1
immense	1
upward	1
and	1
downward	1
currents	1
within	1
them.	1
Round	1
the	1
edges	1
of	1
the	1
sun-spots	1
rise	1
great	1
tongues	1
of	1
flame.	1
Perhaps	1
the	1
most	1
popularly	1
known	1
fact	1
about	1
sun-spots	1
is	1
that	1
they	1
are	1
somehow	1
connected	1
with	1
what	1
we	1
call	1
magnetic	1
storms	1
on	1
earth.	1
These	1
magnetic	1
storms	1
manifest	1
themselves	1
in	1
interruptions	1
of	1
our	1
telegraphic	1
and	1
telephonic	1
communications,	1
in	1
violent	1
disturbances	1
of	1
the	1
mariner's	1
compass,	1
and	1
in	1
exceptional	1
auroral	1
displays.	1
The	1
connection	1
between	1
the	1
two	1
sets	1
of	1
phenomena	1
cannot	1
be	1
doubted,	1
even	1
although	1
at	1
times	1
there	1
may	1
be	1
a	1
great	1
spot	1
on	1
the	1
sun	1
without	1
any	1
corresponding	1
"magnetic	1
storm"	1
effects	1
on	1
the	1
earth.	1
A	1
surprising	1
fact	1
about	1
sun-spots	1
is	1
that	1
they	1
show	1
definite	1
periodic	1
variations	1
in	1
number.	1
The	1
best-defined	1
period	1
is	1
one	1
of	1
about	1
eleven	1
years.	1
During	1
this	1
period	1
the	1
spots	1
increase	1
to	1
a	1
maximum	1
in	1
number	1
and	1
then	1
diminish	1
to	1
a	1
minimum,	1
the	1
variation	1
being	1
more	1
or	1
less	1
regular.	1
Now	1
this	1
can	1
only	1
mean	1
one	1
thing.	1
To	1
be	1
periodic	1
the	1
spots	1
must	1
have	1
some	1
deep-seated	1
connection	1
with	1
the	1
fundamental	1
facts	1
of	1
the	1
sun's	1
structure	1
and	1
activities.	1
Looked	1
at	1
from	1
this	1
point	1
of	1
view	1
their	1
importance	1
becomes	1
great.	1
