to	1
the	1
magnetic	1
phenomena	1
of	1
the	1
earth	1
and	1
therefore	1
is	1
connected	1
with	1
the	1
electrical	1
influence	1
of	1
the	1
sun.]	1
It	1
is	1
from	1
the	1
study	1
of	1
sun-spots	1
that	1
we	1
have	1
learned	1
that	1
the	1
sun's	1
surface	1
does	1
not	1
appear	1
to	1
rotate	1
all	1
at	1
the	1
same	1
speed.	1
The	1
"equatorial"	1
regions	1
are	1
rotating	1
quicker	1
than	1
regions	1
farther	1
north	1
or	1
south.	1
A	1
point	1
forty-five	1
degrees	1
from	1
the	1
equator	1
seems	1
to	1
take	1
about	1
two	1
and	1
a	1
half	1
days	1
longer	1
to	1
complete	1
one	1
rotation	1
than	1
a	1
point	1
on	1
the	1
equator.	1
This,	1
of	1
course,	1
confirms	1
our	1
belief	1
that	1
the	1
sun	1
cannot	1
be	1
a	1
solid	1
body.	1
What	1
is	1
its	1
composition?	1
We	1
know	1
that	1
there	1
are	1
present,	1
in	1
a	1
gaseous	1
state,	1
such	1
well-known	1
elements	1
as	1
sodium,	1
iron,	1
copper,	1
zinc,	1
and	1
magnesium;	1
indeed,	1
we	1
know	1
that	1
there	1
is	1
practically	1
every	1
element	1
in	1
the	1
sun	1
that	1
we	1
know	1
to	1
be	1
in	1
the	1
earth.	1
How	1
do	1
we	1
know?	1
It	1
is	1
from	1
the	1
photosphere,	1
as	1
has	1
been	1
said,	1
that	1
we	1
have	1
won	1
most	1
of	1
our	1
knowledge	1
of	1
the	1
sun.	1
The	1
instrument	1
used	1
for	1
this	1
purpose	1
is	1
the	1
spectroscope;	1
and	1
before	1
proceeding	1
to	1
deal	1
further	1
with	1
the	1
sun	1
and	1
the	1
source	1
of	1
its	1
energy	1
it	1
will	1
be	1
better	1
to	1
describe	1
this	1
instrument.	1
A	1
WONDERFUL	1
INSTRUMENT	1
AND	1
WHAT	1
IT	1
REVEALS	1
The	1
spectroscope	1
is	1
an	1
instrument	1
for	1
analysing	1
light.	1
So	1
important	1
is	1
it	1
in	1
the	1
revelations	1
it	1
has	1
given	1
us	1
that	1
it	1
will	1
be	1
best	1
to	1
describe	1
it	1
fully.	1
Every	1
substance	1
to	1
be	1
examined	1
must	1
first	1
be	1
made	1
to	1
glow,	1
made	1
luminous;	1
and	1
as	1
nearly	1
everything	1
in	1
the	1
heavens	1
_is_	1
luminous	1
the	1
instrument	1
has	1
a	1
great	1
range	1
in	1
Astronomy.	1
And	1
when	1
we	1
speak	1
of	1
analysing	1
light,	1
we	1
mean	1
that	1
the	1
light	1
may	1
be	1
broken	1
up	1
into	1
waves	1
of	1
different	1
lengths.	1
What	1
we	1
call	1
light	1
is	1
a	1
series	1
of	1
minute	1
waves	1
in	1
ether,	1
and	1
these	1
waves	1
are--measuring	1
them	1
from	1
crest	1
to	1
crest,	1
so	1
to	1
say--of	1
various	1
lengths.	1
Each	1
wave-length	1
corresponds	1
to	1
a	1
colour	1
of	1
the	1
rainbow.	1
The	1
shortest	1
waves	1
give	1
us	1
a	1
sensation	1
of	1
violet	1
colour,	1
and	1
the	1
largest	1
waves	1
cause	1
a	1
sensation	1
of	1
red.	1
The	1
rainbow,	1
in	1
fact,	1
is	1
a	1
sort	1
of	1
natural	1
spectrum.	1
(The	1
meaning	1
of	1
the	1
rainbow	1
is	1
that	1
the	1
moisture-laden	1
air	1
has	1
sorted	1
out	1
these	1
waves,	1
in	1
the	1
sun's	1
light,	1
according	1
to	1
their	1
length.)	1
Now	1
the	1
simplest	1
form	1
of	1
spectroscope	1
is	1
a	1
glass	1
prism--a	1
triangular-shaped	1
piece	1
of	1
glass.	1
If	1
white	1
light	1
(sunlight,	1
for	1
example)	1
passes	1
through	1
a	1
glass	1
prism,	1
we	1
see	1
a	1
series	1
of	1
rainbow-tinted	1
colours.	1
Anyone	1
can	1
notice	1
this	1
effect	1
when	1
sunlight	1
is	1
shining	1
through	1
any	1
kind	1
of	1
cut	1
glass--the	1
stopper	1
of	1
a	1
wine	1
decanter,	1
for	1
instance.	1
If,	1
instead	1
of	1
catching	1
with	1
the	1
eye	1
the	1
coloured	1
lights	1
as	1
they	1
emerge	1
from	1
the	1
glass	1
prism,	1
we	1
allow	1
them	1
to	1
fall	1
on	1
a	1
screen,	1
we	1
shall	1
find	1
that	1
they	1
pass,	1
by	1
continuous	1
gradations,	1
from	1
red	1
at	1
the	1
