THE	1
STELLAR	1
UNIVERSE	1
§	1
1	1
The	1
immensity	1
of	1
the	1
Stellar	1
Universe,	1
as	1
we	1
have	1
seen,	1
is	1
beyond	1
our	1
apprehension.	1
The	1
sun	1
is	1
nothing	1
more	1
than	1
a	1
very	1
ordinary	1
star,	1
perhaps	1
an	1
insignificant	1
one.	1
There	1
are	1
stars	1
enormously	1
greater	1
than	1
the	1
sun.	1
One	1
such,	1
Betelgeux,	1
has	1
recently	1
been	1
measured,	1
and	1
its	1
diameter	1
is	1
more	1
than	1
300	1
times	1
that	1
of	1
the	1
sun.	1
The	1
Evolution	1
of	1
Stars	1
The	1
proof	1
of	1
the	1
similarity	1
between	1
our	1
sun	1
and	1
the	1
stars	1
has	1
come	1
to	1
us	1
through	1
the	1
spectroscope.	1
The	1
elements	1
that	1
we	1
find	1
by	1
its	1
means	1
in	1
the	1
sun	1
are	1
also	1
found	1
in	1
the	1
same	1
way	1
in	1
the	1
stars.	1
Matter,	1
says	1
the	1
spectroscope,	1
is	1
essentially	1
the	1
same	1
everywhere,	1
in	1
the	1
earth	1
and	1
the	1
sun,	1
in	1
the	1
comet	1
that	1
visits	1
us	1
once	1
in	1
a	1
thousand	1
years,	1
in	1
the	1
star	1
whose	1
distance	1
is	1
incalculable,	1
and	1
in	1
the	1
great	1
clouds	1
of	1
"fire-mist"	1
that	1
we	1
call	1
nebulæ	1
In	1
