the	1
evolution	1
of	1
the	1
stars	1
let	1
us	1
keep	1
two	1
points	1
clearly	1
in	1
mind.	1
The	1
starting-point,	1
the	1
nebula,	1
is	1
no	1
figment	1
of	1
the	1
scientific	1
imagination.	1
Hundreds	1
of	1
thousands	1
of	1
nebulæbesides	1
even	1
vaster	1
irregular	1
stretches	1
of	1
nebulous	1
matter,	1
exist	1
in	1
the	1
heavens.	1
But	1
the	1
stages	1
of	1
the	1
evolution	1
of	1
this	1
stuff	1
into	1
stars	1
are	1
very	1
largely	1
a	1
matter	1
of	1
speculation.	1
Possibly	1
there	1
is	1
more	1
than	1
one	1
line	1
of	1
evolution,	1
and	1
the	1
various	1
theories	1
may	1
be	1
reconciled.	1
And	1
this	1
applies	1
also	1
to	1
the	1
theories	1
of	1
the	1
various	1
stages	1
through	1
which	1
the	1
stars	1
themselves	1
pass	1
on	1
their	1
way	1
to	1
extinction.	1
The	1
light	1
of	1
about	1
a	1
quarter	1
of	1
a	1
million	1
stars	1
has	1
been	1
analysed	1
in	1
the	1
spectroscope,	1
and	1
it	1
is	1
found	1
that	1
they	1
fall	1
into	1
about	1
a	1
dozen	1
classes	1
which	1
generally	1
correspond	1
to	1
stages	1
in	1
their	1
evolution	1
(Fig.	1
21).	1
The	1
Age	1
of	1
Stars	1
In	1
its	1
main	1
lines	1
the	1
spectrum	1
of	1
a	1
star	1
corresponds	1
to	1
its	1
colour,	1
and	1
we	1
may	1
roughly	1
group	1
the	1
stars	1
into	1
red,	1
yellow,	1
and	1
white.	1
This	1
is	1
also	1
the	1
order	1
of	1
increasing	1
temperature,	1
the	1
red	1
stars	1
being	1
the	1
coolest	1
and	1
the	1
white	1
stars	1
the	1
hottest.	1
We	1
might	1
therefore	1
imagine	1
that	1
the	1
white	1
stars	1
are	1
the	1
youngest,	1
and	1
that	1
as	1
they	1
grow	1
older	1
and	1
cooler	1
they	1
become	1
yellowish,	1
then	1
red,	1
and	1
finally	1
become	1
invisible--just	1
as	1
a	1
cooling	1
