THE	1
SHAPE	1
OF	1
OUR	1
UNIVERSE	1
§	1
4	1
Our	1
Universe	1
a	1
Spiral	1
Nebula	1
What	1
is	1
the	1
shape	1
of	1
our	1
universe,	1
and	1
what	1
are	1
its	1
dimensions?	1
This	1
is	1
a	1
tremendous	1
question	1
to	1
ask.	1
It	1
is	1
like	1
asking	1
an	1
intelligent	1
insect,	1
living	1
on	1
a	1
single	1
leaf	1
in	1
the	1
midst	1
of	1
a	1
great	1
Brazilian	1
forest,	1
to	1
say	1
what	1
is	1
the	1
shape	1
and	1
size	1
of	1
the	1
forest.	1
Yet	1
man's	1
ingenuity	1
has	1
proved	1
equal	1
to	1
giving	1
an	1
answer	1
even	1
to	1
this	1
question,	1
and	1
by	1
a	1
method	1
exactly	1
similar	1
to	1
that	1
which	1
would	1
be	1
adopted	1
by	1
the	1
insect.	1
Suppose,	1
for	1
instance,	1
that	1
the	1
forest	1
was	1
shaped	1
as	1
an	1
elongated	1
oval,	1
and	1
the	1
insect	1
lived	1
on	1
a	1
tree	1
near	1
the	1
centre	1
of	1
the	1
oval.	1
If	1
the	1
trees	1
were	1
approximately	1
equally	1
spaced	1
from	1
one	1
another	1
they	1
would	1
appear	1
much	1
denser	1
along	1
the	1
length	1
of	1
the	1
oval	1
than	1
across	1
its	1
width.	1
This	1
is	1
the	1
simple	1
consideration	1
that	1
has	1
guided	1
astronomers	1
in	1
determining	1
the	1
shape	1
of	1
our	1
stellar	1
universe.	1
There	1
is	1
one	1
direction	1
in	1
the	1
heavens	1
along	1
which	1
the	1
stars	1
appear	1
denser	1
than	1
in	1
the	1
directions	1
at	1
right	1
angles	1
to	1
it.	1
That	1
direction	1
is	1
the	1
direction	1
in	1
which	1
we	1
look	1
towards	1
the	1
Milky	1
Way.	1
If	1
we	1
count	1
the	1
number	1
of	1
stars	1
visible	1
all	1
over	1
the	1
heavens,	1
we	1
find	1
they	1
become	1
more	1
and	1
more	1
numerous	1
as	1
we	1
approach	1
the	1
Milky	1
Way.	1
As	1
we	1
go	1
farther	1
and	1
farther	1
from	1
the	1
Milky	1
Way	1
the	1
stars	1
thin	1
out	1
until	1
they	1
reach	1
a	1
maximum	1
sparseness	1
in	1
directions	1
at	1
right	1
angles	1
to	1
the	1
plane	1
of	1
the	1
Milky	1
Way.	1
We	1
may	1
consider	1
the	1
Milky	1
Way	1
to	1
form,	1
as	1
it	1
were,	1
the	1
equator	1
of	1
our	1
system,	1
and	1
the	1
line	1
at	1
right	1
angles	1
to	1
point	1
to	1
the	1
north	1
and	1
south	1
poles.	1
Our	1
system,	1
in	1
fact,	1
is	1
shaped	1
something	1
like	1
a	1
lens,	1
and	1
our	1
sun	1
is	1
situated	1
near	1
the	1
centre	1
of	1
this	1
lens.	1
In	1
the	1
remoter	1
part	1
of	1
this	1
lens,	1
near	1
its	1
edge,	1
or	1
possibly	1
outside	1
it	1
altogether,	1
lies	1
the	1
great	1
series	1
of	1
star	1
clouds	1
which	1
make	1
up	1
the	1
Milky	1
Way.	1
All	1
the	1
stars	1
are	1
in	1
motion	1
within	1
this	1
system,	1
but	1
the	1
very	1
remarkable	1
discovery	1
has	1
been	1
made	1
that	1
these	1
motions	1
are	1
not	1
entirely	1
random.	1
The	1
great	1
majority	1
of	1
the	1
stars	1
whose	1
motions	1
can	1
be	1
measured	1
fall	1
into	1
two	1
groups	1
drifting	1
past	1
one	1
another	1
in	1
opposite	1
directions.	1
The	1
velocity	1
of	1
one	1
stream	1
relative	1
to	1
the	1
other	1
is	1
about	1
twenty-five	1
miles	1
per	1
second.	1
The	1
stars	1
forming	1
these	1
two	1
groups	1
are	1
thoroughly	1
well	1
mixed;	1
it	1
is	1
not	1
a	1
case	1
of	1
an	1
inner	1
stream	1
going	1
one	1
way	1
and	1
an	1
outer	1
stream	1
the	1
other.	1
But	1
there	1
are	1
not	1
quite	1
as	1
many	1
stars	1
going	1
one	1
way	1
as	1
the	1
other.	1
For	1
