and	1
are	1
subject	1
to	1
further	1
revision.	1
A	1
"light-year"	1
is	1
the	1
distance	1
that	1
light,	1
travelling	1
at	1
the	1
rate	1
of	1
186,000	1
miles	1
per	1
second,	1
would	1
cover	1
in	1
one	1
year.]	1
In	1
this	1
simple	1
outline	1
we	1
have	1
not	1
touched	1
on	1
some	1
of	1
the	1
more	1
debatable	1
questions	1
that	1
engage	1
the	1
attention	1
of	1
modern	1
astronomers.	1
Many	1
of	1
these	1
questions	1
have	1
not	1
yet	1
passed	1
the	1
controversial	1
stage;	1
out	1
of	1
these	1
will	1
emerge	1
the	1
astronomy	1
of	1
the	1
future.	1
But	1
we	1
have	1
seen	1
enough	1
to	1
convince	1
us	1
that,	1
whatever	1
advances	1
the	1
future	1
holds	1
in	1
store,	1
the	1
science	1
of	1
the	1
heavens	1
constitutes	1
one	1
of	1
the	1
most	1
important	1
stones	1
in	1
the	1
wonderful	1
fabric	1
of	1
human	1
knowledge.	1
ASTRONOMICAL	1
INSTRUMENTS	1
§	1
1	1
The	1
Telescope	1
The	1
instruments	1
used	1
in	1
modern	1
astronomy	1
are	1
amongst	1
the	1
finest	1
triumphs	1
of	1
mechanical	1
skill	1
in	1
the	1
world.	1
In	1
a	1
great	1
modern	1
observatory	1
the	1
different	1
instruments	1
are	1
to	1
be	1
counted	1
by	1
the	1
score,	1
but	1
there	1
are	1
two	1
which	1
stand	1
out	1
pre-eminent	1
as	1
the	1
fundamental	1
instruments	1
of	1
modern	1
astronomy.	1
These	1
instruments	1
are	1
the	1
telescope	1
and	1
the	1
spectroscope,	1
and	1
without	1
them	1
astronomy,	1
as	1
we	1
know	1
it,	1
could	1
not	1
exist.	1
There	1
is	1
still	1
some	1
dispute	1
as	1
to	1
where	1
and	1
when	1
the	1
first	1
telescope	1
was	1
constructed;	1
as	1
an	1
astronomical	1
instrument,	1
however,	1
it	1
dates	1
from	1
the	1
time	1
of	1
the	1
great	1
Italian	1
scientist	1
Galileo,	1
who,	1
with	1
a	1
very	1
small	1
and	1
imperfect	1
telescope	1
of	1
his	1
own	1
invention,	1
first	1
observed	1
the	1
spots	1
on	1
the	1
sun,	1
the	1
mountains	1
of	1
the	1
moon,	1
and	1
the	1
chief	1
four	1
satellites	1
of	1
Jupiter.	1
A	1
good	1
pair	1
of	1
modern	1
binoculars	1
is	1
superior	1
to	1
this	1
early	1
instrument	1
of	1
Galileo's,	1
and	1
the	1
history	1
of	1
telescope	1
construction,	1
from	1
that	1
primitive	1
instrument	1
to	1
the	1
modern	1
giant	1
recently	1
erected	1
on	1
Mount	1
Wilson,	1
California,	1
is	1
an	1
exciting	1
chapter	1
in	1
human	1
progress.	1
But	1
the	1
early	1
instruments	1
have	1
only	1
an	1
historic	1
interest:	1
the	1
era	1
of	1
modern	1
telescopes	1
begins	1
in	1
the	1
nineteenth	1
century.	1
During	1
the	1
last	1
century	1
telescope	1
construction	1
underwent	1
an	1
unprecedented	1
development.	1
An	1
immense	1
amount	1
of	1
interest	1
was	1
taken	1
in	1
the	1
construction	1
of	1
large	1
telescopes,	1
and	1
the	1
different	1
countries	1
of	1
the	1
world	1
entered	1
on	1
an	1
exciting	1
race	1
to	1
produce	1
the	1
most	1
powerful	1
possible	1
instruments.	1
Besides	1
this	1
rivalry	1
of	1
different	1
countries	1
there	1
was	1
a	1
rivalry	1
of	1
methods.	1
The	1
telescope	1
developed	1
along	1
two	1
different	1
lines,	1
and	1
each	1
of	1
these	1
two	1
types	1
has	1
its	1
partisans	1
at	1
the	1
present	1
day.	1
These	1
types	1
are	1
known	1
as	1
_refractors_	1
and	1
_reflectors_,	1
and	1
it	1
is	1
necessary	1
to	1
mention,	1
briefly,	1
the	1
principles	1
employed	1
in	1
each.	1
The	1
_refractor_	1
is	1
the	1
ordinary,	1
familiar	1
type	1
of	1
telescope.	1
It	1
consists,	1
essentially,	1
of	1
a	1
large	1
lens	1
at	1
one	1
end	1
of	1
a	1
tube,	1
and	1
a	1
small	1
lens,	1
called	1
the	1
eye-piece,	1
at	1
the	1
other.	1
The	1
function	1
of	1
the	1
large	1
lens	1
is	1
to	1
act	1
as	1
a	1
sort	1
of	1
gigantic	1
eye.	1
It	1
collects	1
a	1
large	1
amount	1
of	1
light,	1
an	1
amount	1
proportional	1
to	1
its	1
size,	1
and	1
brings	1
this	1
light	1
to	1
a	1
focus	1
within	1
the	1
tube	1
of	1
the	1
telescope.	1
It	1
thus	1
produces	1
a	1
small	1
but	1
bright	1
image,	1
and	1
the	1
eye-piece	1
magnifies	1
this	1
image.	1
In	1
the	1
_reflector_,	1
instead	1
of	1
a	1
large	1
lens	1
at	1
the	1
top	1
of	1
the	1
tube,	1
a	1
large	1
mirror	1
is	1
placed	1
at	1
the	1
bottom.	1
This	1
mirror	1
is	1
so	1
shaped	1
as	1
to	1
reflect	1
the	1
light	1
that	1
falls	1
on	1
it	1
to	1
a	1
focus,	1
whence	1
the	1
light	1
is	1
again	1
led	1
to	1
an	1
eye-piece.	1
Thus	1
the	1
refractor	1
and	1
the	1
reflector	1
differ	1
chiefly	1
in	1
their	1
manner	1
of	1
gathering	1
light.	1
The	1
powerfulness	1
of	1
the	1
telescope	1
depends	1
on	1
the	1
size	1
of	1
the	1
light-gatherer.	1
A	1
telescope	1
with	1
a	1
lens	1
four	1
inches	1
in	1
diameter	1
is	1
four	1
times	1
as	1
powerful	1
as	1
the	1
one	1
with	1
a	1
lens	1
two	1
inches	1
in	1
diameter,	1
for	1
the	1
amount	1
of	1
light	1
gathered	1
obviously	1
depends	1
on	1
the	1
_area_	1
of	1
the	1
lens,	1
and	1
the	1
area	1
varies	1
as	1
the	1
_square_	1
of	1
the	1
diameter.	1
The	1
largest	1
telescopes	1
at	1
present	1
in	1
existence	1
are	1
_reflectors_.	1
It	1
is	1
much	1
easier	1
to	1
construct	1
a	1
very	1
large	1
mirror	1
than	1
to	1
construct	1
a	1
very	1
large	1
lens;	1
it	1
is	1
also	1
cheaper.	1
A	1
mirror	1
is	1
more	1
likely	1
to	1
get	1
out	1
of	1
order	1
than	1
is	1
a	1
lens,	1
however,	1
and	1
any	1
irregularity	1
in	1
the	1
shape	1
of	1
a	1
mirror	1
produces	1
a	1
greater	1
distorting	1
effect	1
than	1
in	1
a	1
lens.	1
A	1
refractor	1
is	1
also	1
more	1
convenient	1
to	1
handle	1
than	1
is	1
a	1
reflector.	1
For	1
these	1
reasons	1
great	1
refractors	1
are	1
still	1
made,	1
but	1
the	1
largest	1
of	1
them,	1
the	1
great	1
Yerkes'	1
refractor,	1
is	1
much	1
smaller	1
than	1
the	1
greatest	1
reflector,	1
the	1
one	1
on	1
Mount	1
Wilson,	1
California.	1
The	1
lens	1
of	1
the	1
Yerkes'	1
refractor	1
measures	1
three	1
feet	1
four	1
inches	1
in	1
diameter,	1
whereas	1
the	1
Mount	1
Wilson	1
reflector	1
has	1
a	1
diameter	1
of	1
no	1
less	1
than	1
eight	1
feet	1
four	1
inches.	1
[Illustration:	1
