passes,	1
the	1
star	1
which	1
was	1
too	1
faint	1
to	1
make	1
a	1
perceptible	1
impression	1
on	1
the	1
plate	1
goes	1
on	1
affecting	1
it	1
until	1
finally	1
it	1
makes	1
an	1
impression	1
which	1
can	1
be	1
made	1
visible.	1
In	1
this	1
way	1
the	1
photographic	1
plate	1
reveals	1
to	1
us	1
phenomena	1
in	1
the	1
heavens	1
which	1
cannot	1
be	1
seen	1
even	1
through	1
the	1
most	1
powerful	1
telescopes.	1
Telescopes	1
of	1
the	1
kind	1
we	1
have	1
been	1
discussing,	1
telescopes	1
for	1
exploring	1
the	1
heavens,	1
are	1
mounted	1
_equatorially_;	1
that	1
is	1
to	1
say,	1
they	1
are	1
mounted	1
on	1
an	1
inclined	1
pillar	1
parallel	1
to	1
the	1
axis	1
of	1
the	1
earth	1
so	1
that,	1
by	1
rotating	1
round	1
this	1
pillar,	1
the	1
telescope	1
is	1
enabled	1
to	1
follow	1
the	1
apparent	1
motion	1
of	1
a	1
star	1
due	1
to	1
the	1
rotation	1
of	1
the	1
earth.	1
This	1
motion	1
is	1
effected	1
by	1
clock-work,	1
so	1
that,	1
once	1
adjusted	1
on	1
a	1
star,	1
and	1
the	1
clock-work	1
started,	1
the	1
telescope	1
remains	1
adjusted	1
on	1
that	1
star	1
for	1
any	1
length	1
of	1
time	1
that	1
is	1
desired.	1
But	1
a	1
great	1
official	1
observatory,	1
such	1
as	1
Greenwich	1
Observatory	1
or	1
the	1
Observatory	1
at	1
Paris,	1
also	1
has	1
_transit_	1
instruments,	1
or	1
telescopes	1
smaller	1
than	1
the	1
