_Nautical	1
Almanac_	1
and	1
the	1
_Connaissance	1
du	1
Temps_	1
would	1
be	1
robbed	1
of	1
the	1
greater	1
part	1
of	1
their	1
importance.	1
§	1
2	1
The	1
Spectroscope	1
We	1
have	1
already	1
learnt	1
something	1
of	1
the	1
principles	1
of	1
the	1
spectroscope,	1
the	1
instrument	1
which,	1
by	1
making	1
it	1
possible	1
to	1
learn	1
the	1
actual	1
constitution	1
of	1
the	1
stars,	1
has	1
added	1
a	1
vast	1
new	1
domain	1
to	1
astronomy.	1
In	1
the	1
simplest	1
form	1
of	1
this	1
instrument	1
the	1
analysing	1
portion	1
consists	1
of	1
a	1
single	1
prism.	1
Unless	1
the	1
prism	1
is	1
very	1
large,	1
however,	1
only	1
a	1
small	1
degree	1
of	1
dispersion	1
is	1
obtained.	1
It	1
is	1
obviously	1
desirable,	1
for	1
accurate	1
analytical	1
work,	1
that	1
the	1
dispersion--that	1
is,	1
the	1
separation	1
of	1
the	1
different	1
parts	1
of	1
the	1
spectrum--should	1
be	1
as	1
great	1
as	1
possible.	1
The	1
dispersion	1
can	1
be	1
increased	1
by	1
using	1
a	1
large	1
number	1
of	1
prisms,	1
the	1
light	1
emerging	1
from	1
the	1
first	1
prism,	1
entering	1
the	1
second,	1
and	1
so	1
on.	1
In	1
this	1
way	1
each	1
prism	1
produces	1
its	1
own	1
dispersive	1
effect	1
and,	1
when	1
a	1
number	1
of	1
prisms	1
are	1
employed,	1
the	1
final	1
dispersion	1
is	1
considerable.	1
A	1
considerable	1
amount	1
of	1
light	1
is	1
absorbed	1
in	1
this	1
way,	1
however,	1
so	1
that	1
unless	1
our	1
primary	1
source	1
of	1
light	1
is	1
very	1
strong,	1
the	1
final	1
spectrum	1
will	1
be	1
very	1
feeble	1
and	1
hard	1
to	1
decipher.	1
Another	1
way	1
