Evolution	1
of	1
the	1
Voice	1
The	1
first	1
use	1
of	1
the	1
voice	1
was	1
probably	1
that	1
indicated	1
by	1
our	1
frogs	1
and	1
toads--it	1
serves	1
as	1
a	1
sex-call.	1
That	1
is	1
the	1
meaning	1
of	1
the	1
trumpeting	1
with	1
which	1
frogs	1
herald	1
the	1
spring,	1
and	1
it	1
is	1
often	1
only	1
in	1
the	1
males	1
that	1
the	1
voice	1
is	1
well	1
developed.	1
But	1
if	1
we	1
look	1
forward,	1
past	1
Amphibians	1
altogether,	1
we	1
find	1
the	1
voice	1
becoming	1
a	1
maternal	1
call	1
helping	1
to	1
secure	1
the	1
safety	1
of	1
the	1
young--a	1
use	1
very	1
obvious	1
when	1
young	1
birds	1
squat	1
motionless	1
at	1
the	1
sound	1
of	1
the	1
parent's	1
danger-note.	1
Later	1
on,	1
probably,	1
the	1
voice	1
became	1
an	1
infantile	1
call,	1
as	1
when	1
the	1
unhatched	1
crocodile	1
pipes	1
from	1
within	1
the	1
deeply	1
buried	1
egg,	1
signalling	1
to	1
the	1
mother	1
that	1
it	1
is	1
time	1
to	1
be	1
unearthed.	1
Higher	1
still	1
the	1
voice	1
expresses	1
emotion,	1
as	1
in	1
the	1
song	1
of	1
birds,	1
often	1
outside	1
the	1
limits	1
of	1
the	1
breeding	1
time.	1
Later	1
still,	1
particular	1
sounds	1
become	1
words,	1
signifying	1
particular	1
things	1
or	1
feelings,	1
such	1
as	1
"food,"	1
"danger,"	1
"home,"	1
"anger,"	1
and	1
"joy."	1
Finally	1
words	1
become	1
a	1
medium	1
of	1
social	1
intercourse	1
and	1
as	1
symbols	1
help	1
to	1
make	1
it	1
possible	1
for	1
man	1
to	1
reason.	1
§	1
2	1
The	1
Early	1
Reptiles	1
In	1
the	1
_Permian_	1
period	1
reptiles	1
appeared,	1
or	1
perhaps	1
one	1
should	1
