II.	1
THE	1
OPEN	1
SEA	1
In	1
great	1
contrast	1
to	1
the	1
narrow,	1
crowded,	1
difficult	1
conditions	1
of	1
the	1
shore-haunt	1
(littoral	1
area)	1
are	1
the	1
spacious,	1
bountiful,	1
and	1
relatively	1
easygoing	1
conditions	1
of	1
the	1
open	1
sea	1
(pelagic	1
area),	1
which	1
means	1
the	1
well-lighted	1
surface	1
waters	1
quite	1
away	1
from	1
land.	1
Many	1
small	1
organisms	1
have	1
their	1
maximum	1
abundance	1
at	1
about	1
fifty	1
fathoms,	1
so	1
that	1
the	1
word	1
"surface"	1
is	1
to	1
be	1
taken	1
generously.	1
The	1
light	1
becomes	1
very	1
dim	1
at	1
250	1
fathoms,	1
and	1
the	1
open	1
sea,	1
as	1
a	1
zoological	1
haunt,	1
stops	1
with	1
the	1
light.	1
It	1
is	1
hardly	1
necessary	1
to	1
say	1
that	1
the	1
pelagic	1
plants	1
are	1
more	1
abundant	1
near	1
the	1
surface,	1
and	1
that	1
below	1
a	1
certain	1
depth	1
the	1
population	1
consists	1
almost	1
exclusively	1
of	1
animals.	1
Not	1
a	1
few	1
of	1
the	1
animals	1
sink	1
and	1
rise	1
in	1
the	1
water	1
periodically;	1
there	1
are	1
some	1
that	1
come	1
near	1
the	1
surface	1
by	1
day,	1
and	1
others	1
that	1
come	1
near	1
the	1
surface	1
by	1
night.	1
Of	1
great	1
