III.	1
THE	1
DEEP	1
SEA	1
Very	1
different	1
from	1
all	1
the	1
other	1
haunts	1
are	1
the	1
depths	1
of	1
the	1
sea,	1
including	1
the	1
floor	1
of	1
the	1
abysses	1
and	1
the	1
zones	1
of	1
water	1
near	1
the	1
bottom.	1
This	1
haunt,	1
forever	1
unseen,	1
occupies	1
more	1
than	1
a	1
third	1
of	1
the	1
earth's	1
surface,	1
and	1
it	1
is	1
thickly	1
peopled.	1
It	1
came	1
into	1
emphatic	1
notice	1
in	1
connection	1
with	1
the	1
mending	1
of	1
telegraph	1
cables,	1
but	1
the	1
results	1
of	1
the	1
_Challenger_	1
expedition	1
(1873-6)	1
gave	1
the	1
first	1
impressive	1
picture	1
of	1
what	1
was	1
practically	1
a	1
new	1
world.	1
Physical	1
Conditions	1
The	1
average	1
depth	1
of	1
the	1
ocean	1
is	1
about	1
two	1
and	1
a	1
half	1
miles;	1
therefore,	1
since	1
many	1
parts	1
are	1
relatively	1
shallow,	1
there	1
must	1
be	1
enormous	1
depths.	1
A	1
few	1
of	1
these,	1
technically	1
called	1
"deeps,"	1
are	1
about	1
six	1
miles	1
deep,	1
in	1
which	1
Mount	1
Everest	1
would	1
be	1
engulfed.	1
There	1
is	1
enormous	1
pressure	1
in	1
such	1
depths;	1
even	1
at	1
2,500	1
fathoms	1
it	1
is	1
two	1
and	1
a	1
half	1
tons	1
on	1
the	1
square	1
inch.	1
The	1
temperature	1
is	1
on	1
and	1
off	1
the	1
freezing-point	1
of	1
fresh	1
water	1
(28°-34°	1
Fahr.),	1
due	1
to	1
the	1
continual	1
sinking	1
down	1
of	1
cold	1
water	1
from	1
the	1
Poles,	1
especially	1
from	1
the	1
South.	1
Apart	1
