VII	1
THE	1
DAWN	1
OF	1
MIND	1
THE	1
DAWN	1
OF	1
MIND	1
In	1
the	1
story	1
of	1
evolution	1
there	1
is	1
no	1
chapter	1
more	1
interesting	1
than	1
the	1
emergence	1
of	1
mind	1
in	1
the	1
animal	1
kingdom.	1
But	1
it	1
is	1
a	1
difficult	1
chapter	1
to	1
read,	1
partly	1
because	1
"mind"	1
cannot	1
be	1
seen	1
or	1
measured,	1
only	1
_inferred_	1
from	1
the	1
outward	1
behaviour	1
of	1
the	1
creature,	1
and	1
partly	1
because	1
it	1
is	1
almost	1
impossible	1
to	1
avoid	1
reading	1
ourselves	1
into	1
the	1
much	1
simpler	1
animals.	1
§	1
1	1
Two	1
Extremes	1
to	1
be	1
Avoided	1
The	1
one	1
extreme	1
is	1
that	1
of	1
uncritical	1
generosity	1
which	1
credits	1
every	1
animal,	1
like	1
Brer	1
Rabbit--who,	1
by	1
the	1
way,	1
was	1
the	1
hare--with	1
human	1
qualities.	1
The	1
other	1
extreme	1
is	1
that	1
of	1
thinking	1
of	1
the	1
animal	1
as	1
if	1
it	1
were	1
an	1
automatic	1
machine,	1
in	1
the	1
working	1
of	1
which	1
there	1
is	1
no	1
place	1
or	1
use	1
for	1
mind.	1
Both	1
these	1
extremes	1
are	1
to	1
be	1
avoided.	1
When	1
Professor	1
Whitman	1
took	1
the	1
eggs	1
of	1
the	1
Passenger	1
Pigeon	1
(which	1
became	1
extinct	1
not	1
long	1
ago	1
with	1
startling	1
rapidity)	1
and	1
placed	1
them	1
a	1
few	1
inches	1
to	1
one	1
side	1
of	1
the	1
nest,	1
the	1
bird	1
looked	1
a	1
little	1
uneasy	1
and	1
put	1
her	1
beak	1
under	1
her	1
body	1
as	1
if	1
to	1
feel	1
for	1
something	1
that	1
was	1
not	1
there.	1
But	1
she	1
did	1
not	1
try	1
to	1
retrieve	1
her	1
eggs,	1
close	1
at	1
hand	1
as	1
they	1
were.	1
In	1
a	1
short	1
time	1
she	1
flew	1
away	1
altogether.	1
This	1
shows	1
that	1
the	1
mind	1
of	1
the	1
pigeon	1
is	1
in	1
some	1
respects	1
very	1
different	1
from	1
the	1
mind	1
of	1
man.	1
On	1
the	1
other	1
hand,	1
when	1
a	1
certain	1
clever	1
dog,	1
carrying	1
a	1
basket	1
of	1
eggs,	1
with	1
the	1
handle	1
in	1
his	1
mouth,	1
came	1
to	1
a	1
stile	1
which	1
had	1
to	1
be	1
negotiated,	1
he	1
laid	1
the	1
basket	1
on	1
the	1
ground,	1
pushed	1
it	1
gently	1
through	1
a	1
low	1
gap	1
to	1
the	1
other	1
side,	1
and	1
then	1
took	1
a	1
running	1
leap	1
over.	1
We	1
dare	1
not	1
talk	1
of	1
this	1
dog	1
as	1
an	1
automatic	1
machine.	1
A	1
Caution	1
in	1
Regard	1
to	1
Instinct	1
In	1
studying	1
the	1
behaviour	1
of	1
animals,	1
which	1
is	1
the	1
only	1
way	1
of	1
getting	1
at	1
their	1
mind,	1
for	1
it	1
is	1
only	1
of	1
our	1
own	1
mind	1
that	1
we	1
have	1
direct	1
knowledge,	1
it	1
is	1
essential	1
to	1
give	1
prominence	1
to	1
the	1
fact	1
that	1
there	1
has	1
been	1
throughout	1
the	1
evolution	1
of	1
living	1
creatures	1
a	1
strong	1
tendency	1
to	1
enregister	1
or	1
engrain	1
capacities	1
of	1
doing	1
things	1
effectively.	1
Thus	1
certain	1
abilities	1
come	1
to	1
be	1
inborn;	1
they	1
are	1
parts	1
of	1
the	1
inheritance,	1
which	1
will	1
express	1
themselves	1
whenever	1
the	1
appropriate	1
trigger	1
is	1
pulled.	1
The	1
newly	1
born	1
child	1
does	1
not	1
require	1
to	1
learn	1
its	1
breathing	1
movements,	1
as	1
it	1
afterwards	1
requires	1
to	1
learn	1
its	1
walking	1
movements.	1
The	1
ability	1
to	1
go	1
through	1
the	1
breathing	1
movements	1
is	1
inborn,	1
engrained,	1
enregistered.	1
In	1
other	1
words,	1
there	1
are	1
hereditary	1
pre-arrangements	1
of	1
nerve-cells	1
and	1
muscle-cells	1
which	1
come	1
into	1
activity	1
almost	1
as	1
easily	1
as	1
the	1
beating	1
of	1
the	1
heart.	1
In	1
a	1
minute	1
or	1
two	1
the	1
newborn	1
pigling	1
creeps	1
close	1
to	1
its	1
mother	1
and	1
sucks	1
milk.	1
It	1
has	1
not	1
to	1
learn	1
how	1
to	1
do	1
this	1
any	1
more	1
than	1
we	1
have	1
to	1
learn	1
to	1
cough	1
or	1
sneeze.	1
Thus	1
animals	1
have	1
many	1
useful	1
ready-made,	1
or	1
almost	1
ready-made,	1
capacities	1
of	1
doing	1
apparently	1
clever	1
things.	1
In	1
simple	1
cases	1
of	1
these	1
inborn	1
pre-arrangements	1
we	1
speak	1
of	1
reflex	1
actions;	1
in	1
more	1
complicated	1
cases,	1
of	1
instinctive	1
behaviour.	1
Now	1
the	1
caution	1
is	1
this,	1
that	1
while	1
these	1
inborn	1
capacities	1
usually	1
work	1
well	1
in	1
natural	1
conditions,	1
they	1
sometimes	1
work	1
badly	1
when	1
the	1
ordinary	1
routine	1
is	1
disturbed.	1
We	1
see	1
this	1
when	1
a	1
pigeon	1
continues	1
sitting	1
for	1
many	1
days	1
on	1
an	1
empty	1
nest,	1
or	1
when	1
it	1
fails	1
to	1
retrieve	1
its	1
eggs	1
only	1
two	1
inches	1
away.	1
But	1
it	1
would	1
be	1
a	1
mistake	1
to	1
call	1
the	1
pigeon,	1
because	1
of	1
this,	1
an	1
unutterably	1
stupid	1
bird.	1
We	1
have	1
only	1
to	1
think	1
of	1
the	1
achievements	1
of	1
homing	1
pigeons	1
to	1
know	1
that	1
this	1
cannot	1
be	1
true.	1
We	1
must	1
not	1
judge	1
animals	1
in	1
regard	1
to	1
those	1
kinds	1
of	1
behaviour	1
which	1
have	1
been	1
handed	1
over	1
to	1
instinct,	1
and	1
go	1
badly	1
agee	1
when	1
the	1
normal	1
routine	1
is	1
disturbed.	1
In	1
ninety-nine	1
cases	1
out	1
of	1
a	1
hundred	1
the	1
enregistered	1
instinctive	1
capacities	1
work	1
well,	1
and	1
the	1
advantage	1
of	1
their	1
becoming	1
stereotyped	1
was	1
to	1
leave	1
the	1
animal	1
more	1
free	1
for	1
adventures	1
at	1
a	1
higher	1
level.	1
Being	1
"a	1
slave	1
of	1
instinct"	1
may	1
give	1
the	1
animal	1
a	1
security	1
that	1
enables	1
it	1
to	1
discover	1
some	1
new	1
home	1
or	1
new	1
food	1
or	1
new	1
joy.	1
Somewhat	1
in	1
the	1
same	1
way,	1
a	1
man	1
of	1
methodical	1
habits,	1
which	1
he	1
has	1
himself	1
established,	1
may	1
gain	1
leisure	1
to	1
make	1
some	1
new	1
departure	1
of	1
racial	1
profit.	1
