life	1
of	1
the	1
race	1
they	1
are	1
illustrated	1
by	1
reflex	1
actions	1
and	1
instinctive	1
capacities.	1
Body	1
and	1
Mind	1
We	1
must	1
not	1
shirk	1
the	1
very	1
difficult	1
question	1
of	1
the	1
relation	1
between	1
the	1
bodily	1
and	1
the	1
mental	1
side	1
of	1
behaviour.	1
(_a_)	1
Some	1
great	1
thinkers	1
have	1
taught	1
that	1
the	1
mind	1
is	1
a	1
reality	1
by	1
itself	1
which	1
plays	1
upon	1
the	1
instrument	1
of	1
the	1
brain	1
and	1
body.	1
As	1
the	1
instrument	1
gets	1
worn	1
and	1
dusty	1
the	1
playing	1
is	1
not	1
so	1
good	1
as	1
it	1
once	1
was,	1
but	1
the	1
player	1
is	1
still	1
himself.	1
This	1
theory	1
of	1
the	1
essential	1
independence	1
of	1
the	1
mind	1
is	1
a	1
very	1
beautiful	1
one,	1
but	1
those	1
who	1
like	1
it	1
when	1
applied	1
to	1
themselves	1
are	1
not	1
always	1
so	1
fond	1
of	1
it	1
when	1
it	1
is	1
applied	1
to	1
other	1
intelligent	1
creatures	1
like	1
rooks	1
and	1
elephants.	1
It	1
may	1
be,	1
however,	1
that	1
there	1
is	1
a	1
gradual	1
emancipation	1
of	1
the	1
mind	1
which	1
has	1
gone	1
furthest	1
in	1
Man	1
and	1
is	1
still	1
progressing.	1
(_b_)	1
Some	1
other	1
thinkers	1
have	1
taught	1
that	1
the	1
inner	1
life	1
of	1
thought	1
and	1
feeling	1
is	1
only,	1
as	1
it	1
were,	1
an	1
echo	1
of	1
the	1
really	1
important	1
activity--that	1
of	1
the	1
body	1
and	1
brain.	1
Ideas	1
are	1
just	1
foam-bells	1
on	1
the	1
hurrying	1
streams	1
and	1
circling	1
