all	1
through	1
our	1
life.	1
They	1
are	1
more	1
than	1
the	1
tickings	1
of	1
the	1
clock;	1
they	1
make	1
the	1
wheels	1
go	1
round.	1
(_c_)	1
There	1
are	1
others	1
who	1
think	1
that	1
the	1
most	1
scientific	1
position	1
is	1
simply	1
to	1
recognise	1
both	1
the	1
bodily	1
and	1
the	1
mental	1
activities	1
as	1
equally	1
important,	1
and	1
so	1
closely	1
interwoven	1
that	1
they	1
cannot	1
be	1
separated.	1
Perhaps	1
they	1
are	1
just	1
the	1
outer	1
and	1
the	1
inner	1
aspects	1
of	1
one	1
reality--the	1
life	1
of	1
the	1
creature.	1
Perhaps	1
they	1
are	1
like	1
the	1
concave	1
and	1
convex	1
curves	1
of	1
a	1
dome,	1
like	1
the	1
two	1
sides	1
of	1
a	1
shield.	1
Perhaps	1
the	1
life	1
of	1
the	1
organism	1
is	1
always	1
a	1
unity,	1
at	1
one	1
time	1
appearing	1
more	1
conspicuously	1
as	1
Mind-body,	1
at	1
another	1
time	1
as	1
Body-mind.	1
The	1
most	1
important	1
fact	1
is	1
that	1
neither	1
aspect	1
can	1
be	1
left	1
out.	1
By	1
no	1
jugglery	1
with	1
words	1
can	1
we	1
get	1
Mind	1
out	1
of	1
Matter	1
and	1
Motion.	1
And	1
since	1
we	1
are	1
in	1
ourselves	1
quite	1
sure	1
of	1
our	1
Mind,	1
we	1
are	1
probably	1
safe	1
in	1
saying	1
that	1
in	1
the	1
beginning	1
was	1
Mind.	1
This	1
is	1
in	1
accordance	1
with	1
Aristotle's	1
saying	1
that	1
there	1
is	1
nothing	1
in	1
the	1
end	1
which	1
was	1
not	1
also	1
in	1
kind	1
present	1
in	1
the	1
beginning--whatever	1
we	1
mean	1
by	1
beginning.	1
In	1
conclusion	1
What	1
has	1
led	1
to	1
the	1
truly	1
wonderful	1
result	1
which	1
we	1
admire	1
in	1
a	1
creature	1
