for	1
instance,	1
were	1
so	1
very	1
hooky	1
that,	1
once	1
they	1
got	1
together,	1
a	1
strong	1
man	1
could	1
not	1
tear	1
them	1
apart.	1
The	1
Greeks	1
thought	1
that	1
the	1
explanation	1
of	1
the	1
universe	1
was	1
that	1
an	1
infinite	1
number	1
of	1
these	1
atoms	1
had	1
been	1
moving	1
and	1
mixing	1
in	1
an	1
infinite	1
space	1
during	1
an	1
infinite	1
time,	1
and	1
had	1
at	1
last	1
hit	1
by	1
chance	1
on	1
the	1
particular	1
combination	1
which	1
is	1
our	1
universe.	1
This	1
was	1
too	1
simple	1
and	1
superficial.	1
The	1
idea	1
of	1
atoms	1
was	1
cast	1
aside,	1
only	1
to	1
be	1
advanced	1
again	1
in	1
various	1
ways.	1
It	1
was	1
the	1
famous	1
Manchester	1
chemist,	1
John	1
Dalton,	1
who	1
restored	1
it	1
in	1
the	1
early	1
years	1
of	1
the	1
nineteenth	1
century.	1
He	1
first	1
definitely	1
formulated	1
the	1
atomic	1
theory	1
as	1
a	1
scientific	1
hypothesis.	1
The	1
whole	1
physical	1
and	1
chemical	1
science	1
of	1
that	1
century	1
was	1
now	1
based	1
upon	1
the	1
atom,	1
and	1
it	1
is	1
quite	1
a	1
mistake	1
to	1
suppose	1
that	1
recent	1
discoveries	1
have	1
discredited	1
"atomism."	1
An	1
atom	1
is	1
the	1
smallest	1
particle	1
of	1
a	1
chemical	1
element.	1
No	1
one	1
has	1
ever	1
seen	1
an	1
atom.	1
Even	1
the	1
wonderful	1
new	1
microscope	1
which	1
has	1
just	1
been	1
invented	1
cannot	1
possibly	1
show	1
us	1
particles	1
of	1
matter	1
which	1
are	1
a	1
million	1
times	1
smaller	1
than	1
the	1
breadth	1
of	1
a	1
hair;	1
for	1
that	1
is	1
the	1
size	1
of	1
atoms.	1
We	1
can	1
weigh	1
them	1
and	1
measure	1
