aspects.	1
Energy	1
is	1
recognised	1
in	1
two	1
forms,	1
kinetic	1
and	1
potential.	1
The	1
form	1
of	1
energy	1
which	1
is	1
most	1
apparent	1
to	1
us	1
is	1
the	1
_energy	1
of	1
motion_;	1
for	1
example,	1
a	1
rolling	1
stone,	1
running	1
water,	1
a	1
falling	1
body,	1
and	1
so	1
on.	1
We	1
call	1
the	1
energy	1
of	1
motion	1
_kinetic	1
energy_.	1
Potential	1
energy	1
is	1
the	1
energy	1
a	1
body	1
has	1
in	1
virtue	1
of	1
its	1
position--it	1
is	1
its	1
capacity,	1
in	1
other	1
words,	1
to	1
acquire	1
kinetic	1
energy,	1
as	1
in	1
the	1
case	1
of	1
a	1
stone	1
resting	1
on	1
the	1
edge	1
of	1
a	1
cliff.	1
Energy	1
may	1
assume	1
different	1
forms;	1
one	1
kind	1
of	1
energy	1
may	1
be	1
converted	1
directly	1
or	1
indirectly	1
into	1
some	1
other	1
form.	1
The	1
energy	1
of	1
burning	1
coal,	1
for	1
example,	1
is	1
converted	1
into	1
heat,	1
and	1
from	1
heat	1
energy	1
we	1
have	1
mechanical	1
energy,	1
such	1
as	1
that	1
manifested	1
by	1
the	1
steam-engine.	1
In	1
this	1
way	1
we	1
can	1
transfer	1
energy	1
from	1
one	1
body	1
to	1
another.	1
There	1
is	1
the	1
energy	1
of	1
the	1
great	1
waterfalls	1
of	1
Niagara,	1
for	1
instance,	1
which	1
are	1
used	1
to	1
supply	1
the	1
energy	1
of	1
huge	1
electric	1
power	1
stations.	1
What	1
Heat	1
is	1
An	1
important	1
fact	1
about	1
energy	1
is,	1
that	1
all	1
energy	1
_tends	1
to	1
take	1
the	1
form	1
of	1
heat	1
energy_.	1
The	1
impact	1
of	1
a	1
falling	1
stone	1
generates	1
heat;	1
a	1
waterfall	1
is	1
hotter	1
at	1
the	1
bottom	1
than	1
at	1
the	1
top--the	1
falling	1
particles	1
of	1
water,	1
on	1
striking	1
the	1
ground,	1
generate	1
heat;	1
and	1
most	1
chemical	1
changes	1
are	1
attended	1
by	1
heat	1
changes.	1
Energy	1
may	1
remain	1
latent	1
indefinitely	1
in	1
a	1
lump	1
of	1
wood,	1
but	1
in	1
combustion	1
it	1
is	1
liberated,	1
and	1
we	1
have	1
heat	1
as	1
a	1
result.	1
The	1
atom	1
of	1
radium	1
or	1
of	1
any	1
other	1
radio-active	1
substance,	1
as	1
it	1
disintegrates,	1
generates	1
heat.	1
"Every	1
hour	1
radium	1
generates	1
sufficient	1
heat	1
to	1
raise	1
the	1
temperature	1
of	1
its	1
own	1
weight	1
of	1
water,	1
from	1
the	1
freezing	1
point	1
to	1
the	1
boiling	1
point."	1
And	1
what	1
is	1
heat?	1
_Heat	1
is	1
molecular	1
motion._	1
The	1
molecules	1
of	1
every	1
substance,	1
as	1
we	1
have	1
seen	1
on	1
a	1
previous	1
page,	1
are	1
in	1
a	1
state	1
of	1
continual	1
motion,	1
and	1
the	1
more	1
vigorous	1
the	1
motion	1
the	1
hotter	1
the	1
body.	1
As	1
wood	1
or	1
coal	1
burns,	1
the	1
invisible	1
molecules	1
of	1
these	1
substances	1
are	1
violently	1
agitated,	1
and	1
give	1
rise	1
to	1
ether	1
waves	1
which	1
our	1
senses	1
interpret	1
as	1
light	1
and	1
heat.	1
In	1
this	1
constant	1
movement	1
of	1
the	1
molecules,	1
then,	1
we	1
have	1
a	1
